Users and Groups in Linux

What is a User?

Linux is a multi-user operating system, which means multiple people can use the same system at the same time â€” each having different access levels and permissions.
To manage this efficiently, Linux uses Users and Groups.

A user is an individual account that can log in and perform actions on the system.
Each user has:

1. A username
2. A user ID (UID)
3. A home directory
4. A default shell
5. Permissions that control what they can access or modify.

ðŸ‘‰ Every userâ€™s information is stored in:
/etc/passwd

create user
sudo useradd username
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What is a Group?

A group is a collection of users.
It allows you to manage permissions for multiple users at once â€” instead of assigning them individually.

ðŸ‘‰ Group information is stored in:
/etc/group

sudo groupadd developers

sudo useradd -m -G developers user1
sudo usermod -aG user2 developers

Important Files
File	Purpose
/etc/passwd->	  Stores user account details
/etc/shadow->	  Stores encrypted passwords
/etc/group ->	  Stores group information
/etc/gshadow->	Stores group passwords and security info

UID/GID->  Unique IDs for tracking

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

commands:

Add a new user     ->	 sudo useradd username	Creates a user account
Set password	     ->  sudo passwd username	Assigns password
Delete a user      ->  sudo userdel username	Removes user
Add a group	       ->  sudo groupadd groupname	Creates a new group
Add user to group	 ->  sudo usermod -aG groupname username	Adds user to a group
Show groups of user->  groups username	Lists all groups a user belongs to
Show all users	   ->  cat /etc/passwd	Lists all system users
Show all groups	   ->  cat /etc/group	Lists all groups

